---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { APPS, SEGMENTS, USE_CASES, allPaths, appBySlug, appPairs, description, pageTitle, siteFromHost } from '../content';
const site = siteFromHost();
const slug = Astro.params.slug || '';
const path = Array.isArray(slug) ? slug.join('/') : slug;
const parts = path.split('/').filter(Boolean);
const title = pageTitle(site, path);
const desc = description(site, path);
function channelApps(){ return APPS.filter(a => a.channels.includes(site.channel) || a.channels.includes('marketing')); }
let valid = allPaths().includes(path);
if (!valid) return Astro.redirect('/');
const pairs = appPairs();
const primaryApps = channelApps().slice(0,12);
const campaignRules = [
  'Write the reason for the text before writing the text itself; if the reason is weak, use email or do not send.',
  'Separate acquisition, cart recovery, launch, replenishment, loyalty, and winback campaigns because each has a different tolerance for urgency.',
  'Protect margin with discount ladders, exclusions for recent buyers, and product-level rules instead of one blanket coupon.',
  'Review opt-outs, replies, and repeat purchase after every major campaign; attributed revenue alone is not a health score.',
  'Give every SMS a destination that matches the promise: checkout, collection, account portal, subscription portal, or concierge support.'
];
const pageKind = parts[0] === 'apps' && parts[1] ? 'app review' : parts[0] === 'compare' && parts[1] ? 'comparison' : parts[0] === 'for' && parts[1] ? 'store-type guide' : parts[0] === 'use-cases' && parts[1] ? 'use-case playbook' : parts[0] === 'alternatives' ? 'alternative guide' : parts[0] === 'apps' ? 'app directory' : parts[0] === 'compare' ? 'comparison hub' : parts[0] === 'for' ? 'store-type hub' : parts[0] === 'use-cases' ? 'use-case hub' : 'SMS guide';
const depthSubject = parts[0] === 'apps' && parts[1] ? appBySlug(parts[1])?.name : parts[0] === 'compare' && parts[1] ? parts[1].split('-vs-').map(appBySlug).map(a=>a?.name).join(' vs ') : parts[0] === 'for' && parts[1] ? SEGMENTS.find(s=>s.slug===parts[1])?.name : parts[0] === 'use-cases' && parts[1] ? USE_CASES.find(u=>u.slug===parts[1])?.name : parts[0] === 'alternatives' ? `${appBySlug((parts[1]||'').replace('-alternative',''))?.name} alternatives` : site.primaryKeyword;
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={desc} site={site} path={`/${path}`}>
  <section class="border-b-2 border-orange-300 py-14"><div class="container"><span class="badge">{site.primaryKeyword} · campaign lab</span><h1 class="hero-title mt-4">{title}</h1><p class="mt-5 max-w-4xl text-xl text-orange-950/80">{desc} The guidance below is written for Shopify marketers who need revenue from SMS without flattening every customer relationship into another flash-sale blast. It emphasizes campaign architecture, segmentation, offer discipline, and the point where email should support or replace a text.</p></div></section>

  {parts[0] === 'apps' && !parts[1] && <section class="container py-12"><div class="mb-8 max-w-4xl"><h2 class="text-3xl font-black">SMS marketing app directory</h2><p class="mt-4 text-orange-950/75">Use this directory as a campaign planning shortlist. The right Shopify SMS marketing app should help the team capture compliant subscribers, personalize by customer and product behavior, send urgent moments quickly, and avoid the lazy habit of discounting every send.</p></div><div class="grid gap-5 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3">{APPS.map((app,i)=><a class="card" href={`/apps/${app.slug}`}><div class="text-sm font-black text-orange-700">#{i+1} · {app.category}</div><h2 class="mt-2 text-2xl font-black text-slate-950">{app.name}</h2><p class="mt-2 text-sm text-orange-950/75">Best for {app.bestFor}.</p><p class="mt-4 text-sm font-black">{app.pricing}</p></a>)}</div></section>}

  {parts[0] === 'apps' && parts[1] && (() => { const app = appBySlug(parts[1])!; return <section class="container grid gap-8 py-12 lg:grid-cols-[1fr_330px]"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>How {app.name} supports Shopify SMS marketing</h2><p>{app.shopifyFit} In the context of <strong>{site.primaryKeyword}</strong>, the buying question is bigger than deliverability or template count. A store needs to know whether {app.name} can support an actual campaign calendar: list growth, welcome offers, product launches, cart recovery, post-purchase messages, replenishment reminders, VIP treatment, holiday pressure, and winback offers.</p><p>The best SMS marketing systems help marketers resist bad habits. They make segmentation obvious, expose message cost, show unsubscribe pressure, and connect Shopify events to clean audiences. If a tool makes it easy to blast everyone but hard to suppress recent buyers, separate high-intent shoppers, or coordinate with email, it may create short-term revenue and long-term fatigue.</p><h2>Best-fit campaign team</h2><p>{app.name} is strongest for {app.bestFor}. Evaluate it by mapping your next ten campaigns into the platform. Can the team build a launch sequence with early access for VIPs, a second message for engaged non-buyers, and exclusions for shoppers who already purchased? Can it handle cart recovery without over-discounting? Can it support post-purchase education without forcing a long text where an email would perform better?</p><h2>Strengths</h2><ul>{app.strengths.map(s=><li>{s}</li>)}</ul><h2>Tradeoffs</h2><ul>{app.limits.map(l=><li>{l}</li>)}</ul><h2>Campaign rollout plan</h2><p>Start with the highest-value moments and write a clear purpose for each. The welcome campaign should set expectations and earn the first purchase. Abandoned checkout should help a shopper return quickly. Browse abandonment should be more cautious, because interest is weaker. Post-purchase should reduce anxiety and introduce the next useful action. Replenishment and winback should rely on product timing and customer history rather than a generic monthly blast.</p><p>Build reporting before the first major send. Review revenue, clicks, replies, unsubscribes, gross margin, and purchases from customers who did not receive the text where possible. A marketing app is only useful if the team can tell whether a campaign created healthy revenue or borrowed demand from a discount-sensitive audience.</p><h2>Final buying guidance</h2><p>Choose {app.name} if it makes your campaign calendar more selective, more measurable, and more connected to Shopify data. Do not choose it merely because the editor looks friendly. For {site.keywordPlural}, the operational winner is the app that helps marketers send fewer low-value texts and more high-intent messages that customers understand immediately.</p></article><aside class="card h-fit"><div class="text-sm font-black uppercase tracking-[.16em] text-orange-700">Marketing snapshot</div><dl class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-sm text-orange-950/80"><div><dt class="font-black text-slate-950">Category</dt><dd>{app.category}</dd></div><div><dt class="font-black text-slate-950">Pricing</dt><dd>{app.pricing}</dd></div><div><dt class="font-black text-slate-950">Best for</dt><dd>{app.bestFor}</dd></div></dl><a class="btn btn-primary mt-6 w-full" href="https://sequenzy.com">Compare with Sequenzy</a></aside></section> })()}

  {parts[0] === 'compare' && !parts[1] && <section class="container py-12"><div class="mb-8 max-w-4xl"><h2 class="text-3xl font-black">SMS marketing app comparisons</h2><p class="mt-4 text-orange-950/75">These matchups focus on campaign operations: acquisition, segmentation, promotion planning, channel coordination, pricing at send volume, and Shopify reporting clarity.</p></div><div class="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3">{pairs.map(([a,b])=><a class="card" href={`/compare/${a.slug}-vs-${b.slug}`}><h2 class="text-xl font-black">{a.name} vs {b.name}</h2><p class="mt-2 text-sm text-orange-950/75">Which is stronger for {site.primaryKeyword.toLowerCase()}?</p></a>)}</div></section>}

  {parts[0] === 'compare' && parts[1] && (() => { const [a,b] = parts[1].split('-vs-').map(appBySlug); return <section class="container py-12"><div class="card overflow-x-auto"><table class="data-table"><thead><tr><th>Criteria</th><th>{a?.name}</th><th>{b?.name}</th><th>Campaign takeaway</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Best fit</td><td>{a?.bestFor}</td><td>{b?.bestFor}</td><td>Start with the campaign calendar, not the brand name.</td></tr><tr><td>Pricing</td><td>{a?.pricing}</td><td>{b?.pricing}</td><td>Estimate costs for launch week, holiday sends, and list growth.</td></tr><tr><td>Primary strength</td><td>{a?.strengths[0]}</td><td>{b?.strengths[0]}</td><td>Reward the tool that protects revenue quality.</td></tr></tbody></table></div><article class="prose-shopify mt-8 card"><h2>Which app is better for Shopify SMS marketing?</h2><p>{a?.name} usually makes more sense when your priority is {a?.bestFor}. {b?.name} becomes more attractive when the store cares more about {b?.bestFor}. The practical answer depends on which campaigns must improve first: subscriber capture, welcome conversion, cart recovery, product launches, loyalty, replenishment, or winback.</p><p>A good comparison should include a simulated month. Put the planned campaigns into both tools and check where the process breaks. Does segmentation require manual exports? Are recent purchasers excluded automatically? Can the team coordinate email education with SMS urgency? Does pricing punish necessary targeting? Can marketers read performance by product, cohort, and offer?</p><h2>Campaign checklist</h2><ul>{campaignRules.map(p=><li>{p}</li>)}</ul><p>When two apps seem similar, prefer the one that reduces careless sending. A platform that encourages restraint, clearer offers, and better Shopify data usage will usually beat a platform that only accelerates blasts.</p></article></section> })()}

  {parts[0] === 'for' && !parts[1] && <section class="container py-12"><div class="mb-8 max-w-4xl"><h2 class="text-3xl font-black">SMS marketing by Shopify category</h2><p class="mt-4 text-orange-950/75">Category context changes cadence, offers, compliance risk, and creative. Pick a store type to tailor the SMS marketing stack.</p></div><div class="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-3">{SEGMENTS.map(s=><a class="card" href={`/for/${s.slug}`}><h2 class="text-xl font-black">{s.name}</h2><p class="mt-2 text-sm text-orange-950/75">Campaign problems: {s.pain}.</p></a>)}</div></section>}
  {parts[0] === 'for' && parts[1] && (() => { const seg=SEGMENTS.find(s=>s.slug===parts[1])!; return <section class="container py-12"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Choosing {site.primaryKeyword} for {seg.name}</h2><p>{seg.name} need campaigns that account for {seg.pain}. That means the SMS marketing app must support more than broad promotional sends. It should help the marketer understand product interest, order history, replenishment or gifting windows, discount sensitivity, and the moments where urgency is helpful instead of pushy.</p><p>Start by listing the campaigns that genuinely fit the category. A launch-heavy brand may need waitlists, VIP early access, inventory alerts, and post-drop follow-up. A replenishment business needs timing, routine education, and subscription-friendly messages. A high-AOV business may need concierge prompts and proof, but far fewer blasts. The app shortlist should change based on that map.</p><h2>Recommended shortlist</h2><ul>{primaryApps.slice(0,7).map(a=><li><a class="link" href={`/apps/${a.slug}`}>{a.name}</a> — {a.bestFor}</li>)}</ul><h2>Campaign design notes</h2><p>For {seg.name}, define one acquisition campaign, one conversion campaign, one post-purchase campaign, and one retention campaign before expanding. Use Shopify data to avoid overlap: recent buyers should not receive the same urgency as prospects, high-value customers should not be treated like coupon hunters, and product-specific buyers should receive messages that reflect what they actually own or considered.</p><p>The best app is the one that makes these distinctions easy for a marketer on a busy week. If the tool requires engineering work or spreadsheet cleanup for every send, the team will eventually default to generic blasts.</p><h2>Measurement plan</h2><p>Measure revenue by campaign, opt-out rate, replies, repeat purchase, average discount, and performance by product or collection. Category pages should be judged by customer behavior after the campaign, not only same-day attributed sales.</p></article></section> })()}

  {parts[0] === 'use-cases' && !parts[1] && <section class="container py-12"><div class="mb-8 max-w-4xl"><h2 class="text-3xl font-black">SMS marketing use cases</h2><p class="mt-4 text-orange-950/75">Each use case below expands into a campaign guide with timing, offer, segmentation, and measurement advice.</p></div><div class="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-3">{USE_CASES.map(u=><a class="card" href={`/use-cases/${u.slug}`}><h2 class="text-xl font-black">{u.name}</h2><p class="mt-2 text-sm text-orange-950/75">Use {site.primaryKeyword.toLowerCase()} to {u.job}.</p></a>)}</div></section>}
  {parts[0] === 'use-cases' && parts[1] && (() => { const u=USE_CASES.find(x=>x.slug===parts[1])!; return <section class="container py-12"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Campaign strategy for {u.name}</h2><p>The purpose of {u.name} is to {u.job}. In a Shopify SMS marketing program, that purpose should determine the trigger, copy, incentive, destination, and suppression logic. SMS should be short and direct, but the strategy behind it should be specific.</p><p>Begin with the audience. Is the customer new, active, lapsed, high-value, discount-sensitive, product-curious, or already subscribed? Then decide whether urgency is legitimate. Cart recovery, back-in-stock, and launch access often justify a text. Long education, broad storytelling, and heavy proof usually belong in email with SMS used only as a concise prompt.</p><h2>Apps to consider</h2><ul>{primaryApps.slice(0,8).map(a=><li><a class="link" href={`/apps/${a.slug}`}>{a.name}</a>: {a.shopifyFit}</li>)}</ul><h2>Execution details</h2><p>Write one primary message, one fallback message, and one exclusion rule. The primary message should state why the customer is receiving it and what to do next. The fallback should avoid repeating the same incentive. The exclusion rule should protect recent purchasers, customers in support conversations, and anyone already engaged through another campaign.</p><h2>Metrics that matter</h2><p>Measure attributed revenue, unsubscribes, reply sentiment, margin after incentives, repeat purchase, and the behavior of customers who received email but not SMS. If {u.name} wins revenue but weakens the list, the campaign needs tighter targeting or a different offer.</p></article></section> })()}

  {parts[0] === 'alternatives' && (() => { const app=appBySlug((parts[1]||'').replace('-alternative',''))!; const alts=APPS.filter(a=>a.slug!==app.slug).slice(0,8); return <section class="container py-12"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Why marketers compare {app.name} alternatives</h2><p>{app.name} can be a serious option, but Shopify teams often look for alternatives when SMS marketing needs change. The issue may be pricing at volume, campaign calendar complexity, weak segmentation, limited email coordination, reporting gaps, or the need for a lighter operating workflow.</p><p>Do not begin an alternative search with a feature checklist copied from a vendor page. Begin with the campaign that is underperforming. If cart recovery is weak, inspect checkout triggers and offer controls. If launches underperform, inspect waitlist capture and VIP segmentation. If replenishment is inconsistent, inspect product timing and customer history. If reporting is confusing, inspect attribution and cohort views.</p><h2>Best alternatives</h2><ul>{alts.map(a=><li><a class="link" href={`/apps/${a.slug}`}>{a.name}</a> — {a.bestFor}</li>)}</ul><h2>Switching rule</h2><p>Switch when the alternative makes an important campaign easier to launch, easier to measure, or cheaper to scale. Do not switch only because the interface is newer. The migration should improve your ability to send relevant texts and coordinate them with email, onsite capture, customer support, and Shopify merchandising.</p><p>Before moving, rebuild one campaign in the candidate app and score the process: audience creation, exclusions, copy, offer, landing path, QA, approval, reporting, and post-campaign learning. A good alternative reduces friction at several of those steps.</p></article></section> })()}

  {parts[0] === 'guides' && <section class="container py-12"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Shopify SMS marketing selection framework</h2><p>Choose {site.primaryKeyword} by matching the app to campaign jobs. Acquisition needs compliant capture and expectation setting. Welcome needs fast first-purchase clarity. Cart recovery needs intent-sensitive timing. Product launches need segmentation and inventory awareness. Retention needs customer history and restraint. Winback needs a reason to return that does not train every shopper to wait for a coupon.</p><p>The framework is: define the campaign moment, prove SMS is the right channel, choose the narrowest useful audience, protect margin, coordinate with email, and review list health after the send. A tool that supports this discipline will outperform a tool that only makes blasting faster.</p><h2>Internal linking map</h2><ul><li><a class="link" href="/apps">All apps</a></li><li><a class="link" href="/compare">Comparison pages</a></li><li><a class="link" href="/use-cases/product-launch">Product launch guide</a></li><li><a class="link" href="/for/beauty">Beauty store guide</a></li></ul><h2>Campaign rules</h2><ul>{campaignRules.map(p=><li>{p}</li>)}</ul></article></section>}

  {parts[0] === 'apps' && parts[1] && (() => { const app = appBySlug(parts[1])!; return <section class="container pb-12"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>{app.name} SMS campaign scoring rubric</h2><p>Score {app.name} against the campaigns a Shopify team will actually send: welcome, abandoned checkout, product launch, replenishment, VIP access, loyalty, and winback. Give credit for consent clarity, quiet-hour controls, Shopify event reliability, segment freshness, recent-buyer exclusions, offer governance, reply handling, and cost visibility at volume.</p><h3>Implementation steps</h3><p>Begin with opt-in source cleanup, then launch one welcome text, one abandoned checkout text, one high-intent launch or back-in-stock campaign, and one retention campaign tied to the catalog. Each text needs a reason, a destination, an exclusion rule, and a measurement plan before copy is written. {app.name} should make these decisions obvious rather than encouraging broad blasts.</p><h3>Migration risks</h3><p>Before switching, test consent import, opt-out sync, keyword handling, phone-number formatting, carrier compliance, time zones, Shopify customer matching, and message costs. Rebuild one campaign in {app.name} and compare the audience count with the current tool. A mismatch can mean recent buyers, unsubscribed customers, or non-consented profiles are being handled incorrectly.</p><h3>Example campaign</h3><p>For abandoned checkout, send a concise reminder while intent is fresh, avoid stacking a discount with email, and suppress anyone who completed purchase or opened a support issue. For a launch, text VIPs first, exclude purchasers from the second blast, and let email carry product education while SMS carries the timely nudge.</p></article></section> })()}

  {parts[0] === 'compare' && parts[1] && (() => { const [a,b] = parts[1].split('-vs-').map(appBySlug); return <section class="container pb-12"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Decision framework for {a?.name} vs {b?.name}</h2><p>Compare both apps by staging the same campaign month: one list-growth offer, one abandoned checkout sequence, one product launch, one category-specific retention message, and one winback attempt. Score setup time, exclusions, cost, consent handling, email coordination, audience clarity, and post-send learning.</p><h3>Tradeoff examples</h3><p>If {a?.name} has stronger segmentation but {b?.name} is faster for broadcasts, decide whether precision or speed is the current constraint. If {b?.name} has lower entry pricing but {a?.name} reduces opt-outs and wasted sends, model net revenue after message costs and discounts. SMS comparisons should reward restraint because fatigue is expensive.</p><h3>Measurement</h3><p>Choose the winner after reviewing revenue per recipient, opt-out rate, reply quality, contribution margin, repeat purchase, and overlap with email. A tool that produces slightly less attributed revenue but protects list health may be the better long-term marketing system.</p></article></section> })()}

  {parts[0] === 'use-cases' && parts[1] && (() => { const u=USE_CASES.find(x=>x.slug===parts[1])!; return <section class="container pb-12"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>{u.name} SMS execution playbook</h2><p>The job is to {u.job}. For SMS, that job must be specific enough to justify an interruption. Write the reason for the message, the audience, the moment, the landing destination, and the stop condition before writing the copy.</p><h3>Message structure</h3><p>Use one direct prompt, one useful context point, and one link. If proof or education takes more space, send it by email and let SMS point to the decision moment. Add suppression for recent buyers, customers in another active campaign, low-margin products, and anyone whose opt-in source promised a different kind of text.</p><h3>Metrics and mistakes</h3><p>Measure revenue per recipient, opt-outs, replies, margin after incentives, repeat purchase, and whether email-only customers behaved similarly. Common mistakes include texting too often, using the same discount for every segment, ignoring quiet hours, repeating an email in shorter form, and continuing after purchase.</p></article></section> })()}

  {parts[0] === 'for' && parts[1] && (() => { const seg=SEGMENTS.find(s=>s.slug===parts[1])!; return <section class="container pb-12"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>SMS advice for {seg.name}</h2><p>{seg.name} need a campaign calendar that accounts for {seg.pain}. SMS should be reserved for moments where timing or access matters: fresh cart intent, limited inventory, reorder windows, VIP previews, delivery-sensitive gifts, or urgent account actions.</p><h3>Campaign priorities</h3><p>Pick one acquisition message, one conversion message, one post-purchase or retention message, and one reactivation message. A fashion store may prioritize drops and size availability. A supplement store may prioritize routine reminders and careful claims. A jewelry store may need gifting deadlines and concierge help. The app should let the operator target those differences cleanly.</p><h3>Risk controls</h3><p>Watch discount dependence, opt-out spikes, campaign overlap, and generic copy. Recent buyers should be protected from broad urgency. High-value customers may deserve access rather than a markdown. Category-specific SMS works when it feels like service, not pressure.</p></article></section> })()}

  <section class="container pb-16"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Campaign lab notes for this page</h2><p>Use this page as a planning document for an SMS marketing program, not as a list of apps to install casually. Shopify SMS marketing becomes profitable when the team knows why a customer is receiving a text, what action the customer can take in one tap, and why the same message should not simply be an email. The app should reinforce that discipline with useful audiences, reliable Shopify events, easy exclusions, and reporting that shows list health as well as sales.</p><p>A practical first month has four stages. First, clean up consent capture and make sure the forms explain what subscribers will receive. Second, rebuild the most important conversion campaign with tight exclusions for recent buyers and customers already in another active flow. Third, add one retention campaign that reflects the business model: replenishment, loyalty, education, a launch waitlist, or a post-purchase next step. Fourth, review unsubscribe pressure, replies, margin, and repeat purchase so the next campaign is sharper rather than louder.</p><p>The strongest marketing teams also define offer rules. A first-purchase incentive should not automatically become a repeat-purchase incentive. VIP customers may deserve early access instead of a bigger coupon. Lapsed customers may need a reason, a product angle, or social proof rather than a desperate discount. A useful app makes those distinctions easier to run without a spreadsheet before every send.</p><p>Move through the site by intent. App pages explain platform fit. Comparison pages show tradeoffs between two choices. Store-type pages translate SMS marketing into category-specific campaign logic. Use-case pages turn one marketing job into a flow structure. The objective is a campaign calendar that customers experience as timely and helpful, not an endless series of identical sale alerts.</p></article></section>
  <section class="bg-orange-100/70 py-14">
    <div class="container grid gap-8 lg:grid-cols-[.7fr_1.3fr]">
      <aside class="card h-fit"><span class="badge">Long campaign brief</span><h2 class="mt-4 text-3xl font-black">How to evaluate this {pageKind} for {depthSubject}</h2><p class="mt-4 text-orange-950/75">This added brief makes the page substantial enough to stand alone as a Shopify SMS planning document, with context for consent, campaign economics, segmentation, and channel restraint.</p></aside>
      <article class="prose-shopify">
        <h2>Start with permission and expectation</h2>
        <p>SMS marketing is different from email because the interruption is sharper and the tolerance for weak messages is lower. Before a Shopify team judges any app, comparison, alternative, store-type guide, or use-case playbook, it should define what subscribers were promised at opt-in. A compliant form is not enough. The customer should understand whether texts will include launches, cart reminders, replenishment prompts, loyalty access, transactional-adjacent support, or occasional offers. When the expectation is clear, every campaign has a standard to meet. When the expectation is vague, even profitable sends can train the audience to ignore or unsubscribe.</p>
        <h2>Campaign architecture for Shopify data</h2>
        <p>The strongest {site.keywordPlural} make Shopify events usable in the campaign builder. Useful SMS audiences often depend on checkout started, cart value, product or collection viewed, product purchased, time since last order, discount history, subscription status, loyalty tier, and whether the customer recently received another campaign. A broad sale alert may create short-term revenue, but the durable program is built from smaller groups: VIPs before the public launch, replenishment candidates near the natural reorder window, cart abandoners with high intent, customers who bought the matching product family, and lapsed buyers with a real reason to return.</p>
        <h2>When SMS should not be the whole message</h2>
        <p>Many Shopify campaigns need both urgency and education. SMS is excellent for a concise prompt, but it is rarely the best place for long ingredient explanations, fit guides, warranty details, comparison tables, or brand storytelling. This {pageKind} should therefore be read alongside the email program. Let email carry the proof and product context, then let SMS point to the moment when action matters. For {depthSubject}, the practical test is whether the tool or strategy helps the marketer decide which part of the campaign belongs in a text, which part belongs in email, and which part should be handled on the product page or account portal.</p>
        <h2>Offer discipline and list health</h2>
        <p>SMS can make discounts feel urgent, so offer rules matter. A first-purchase coupon should not automatically become the default for repeat buyers. Recent purchasers should be excluded from broad urgency unless there is a clear accessory, replenishment, or VIP reason. High-value customers may prefer access, concierge help, or early product information over a deeper markdown. After every campaign, review unsubscribe rate, reply sentiment, revenue per recipient, contribution margin, repeat purchase, and whether customer support saw confusion. Attributed revenue alone can hide list fatigue, especially during holidays or repeated launch cycles.</p>
        <h2>Rollout sequence and QA</h2>
        <p>A careful rollout starts with consent capture, keyword or form sources, welcome text, abandoned checkout, one product-launch campaign, and one retention campaign. Each message needs a destination that matches the promise, a suppression window, a fallback if the first offer is ignored, and a clear owner for post-send review. QA should include links, coupons, UTM tags, segment membership, recent-buyer exclusions, time zones, quiet hours, and coordination with email. If this {pageKind} helps a merchant operate that checklist with less manual cleanup, it is doing useful work for Shopify SMS marketing rather than merely adding another app name to a directory.</p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* HERMES_DEEP_PASS_JULY5 */}
  {parts[0] === 'apps' && parts[1] && (() => { const app = appBySlug(parts[1])!; return <section class="container pb-16"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Operator evidence to collect before trusting {app.name}</h2><p>This {site.primaryKeyword} review should leave a mobile retention owner with evidence, not vibes. Open Shopify and choose five real customer timelines: a new subscriber with no orders, a shopper who abandoned a high-value product, a recent first-time buyer, a repeat buyer who normally purchases on a predictable cycle, and a lapsed customer who once bought during a sale. Then test whether {app.name} can explain what each person should receive next and what they should be excluded from. If the answer depends on a spreadsheet, hidden tag, or agency-only convention, the app is weaker than the demo suggests.</p><p>For this site, the important surface area is popup consent, abandoned checkout, product drops, replenishment, back-in-stock, VIP access, winback, and reply handling. {app.name} earns a stronger score when those jobs live in one understandable operating rhythm. It loses points when it creates a prettier editor but leaves trigger accuracy, consent, product context, suppression, or reporting ambiguous. The practical question is whether a merchant can make a safe change on a busy Thursday before a launch without breaking another journey.</p><p>Ask the vendor to walk through a failure. Inventory is out of stock, a coupon is already attached, a customer purchased on another device, deliverability softened last week, and a campaign is scheduled for the same audience tomorrow. A serious SMS marketing app makes the safe answer visible. A shallow tool still sends because the automation technically qualifies.</p><h3>Evidence checklist</h3><ul><li>Real Shopify customer examples match the intended journeys and exclusions.</li><li>Product, order, consent, discount, and customer-stage fields are visible where the marketer edits the workflow.</li><li>The team can name the owner, review cadence, rollback path, and metric that decides whether the workflow stays live.</li><li>Reporting connects to cost per converted recipient, opt-out rate, reply sentiment, campaign overlap, repeat order behavior, and margin after incentive rather than only platform-attributed revenue.</li></ul></article></section> })()}
  {parts[0] === 'compare' && parts[1] && (() => { const [a,b] = parts[1].split('-vs-').map(appBySlug); return <section class="container pb-16"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Deeper buying test for {a?.name} vs {b?.name}</h2><p>A useful comparison should simulate the next ninety days, not just compare menus. Build the same operating calendar in both tools: one acquisition capture path, one intent-recovery path, one customer education path, one repeat-purchase or reactivation path, and one high-pressure promotion. For each, document the trigger, audience, exclusion, offer, product context, channel coordination, reporting view, and owner. The winner is the tool that makes the calendar easier to run after the onboarding call ends.</p><p>Use {site.primaryKeyword} criteria instead of generic SaaS criteria. The deciding work is popup consent, abandoned checkout, product drops, replenishment, back-in-stock, VIP access, winback, and reply handling. If {a?.name} handles those jobs with fewer manual rules, it deserves the nod even if {b?.name} has a nicer campaign editor. If {b?.name} protects paying for messages that reach the wrong audience or train shoppers to wait for urgent texts better, that matters more than one extra dashboard. Shopify teams do not need abstract power; they need safe changes, cleaner targeting, and revenue that survives margin math.</p><p>Do not let attribution settle the argument by itself. Compare the tools against cost per converted recipient, opt-out rate, reply sentiment, campaign overlap, repeat order behavior, and margin after incentive. Also count team time: setup meetings, QA passes, segment cleanup, creative edits, agency dependency, support tickets, and the cost of fixing mistakes. A cheaper app can become expensive if every sale week requires manual audits. A powerful app can become expensive if nobody trusts the interface enough to keep improving flows.</p><h3>Decision notes to write down</h3><ul><li>Where {a?.name} is clearly safer or faster.</li><li>Where {b?.name} is clearly safer or faster.</li><li>Which customer moment is most valuable for this store right now.</li><li>What migration step would break revenue if rushed.</li></ul></article></section> })()}
  {parts[0] === 'use-cases' && parts[1] && (() => { const useCase = USE_CASES.find((item) => item.slug === parts[1])!; return <section class="container pb-16"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Advanced implementation notes for {useCase.name}</h2><p>{useCase.name} should start with a policy, not a template. Write the commercial rule first: who qualifies, why the message is useful now, what product or order context changes the copy, when the customer should be suppressed, and which other campaigns take priority. Then choose the SMS marketing app that can express that policy without a tangle of manual tags.</p><p>For {site.primaryKeyword}, the hidden work is popup consent, abandoned checkout, product drops, replenishment, back-in-stock, VIP access, winback, and reply handling. A thin setup sends the same message to every eligible profile. A stronger setup changes timing and proof based on the customer: first-time versus repeat buyer, full-price versus coupon buyer, high-AOV versus low-margin cart, subscription versus one-off order, gift purchase versus self purchase, and recent support issue versus clean journey. These differences are where the revenue quality comes from.</p><p>Before launch, run a QA table with at least ten examples. Include recent purchasers, inactive subscribers, VIPs, discount-sensitive shoppers, customers with multiple carts, buyers whose product is out of stock, and people already scheduled for a campaign. Record the expected outcome and the actual outcome. If the app cannot explain a mismatch, fix the rule before sending. After launch, review cost per converted recipient, opt-out rate, reply sentiment, campaign overlap, repeat order behavior, and margin after incentive and one or two customer timelines each week until the workflow behaves predictably.</p><h3>Common pitfalls</h3><ul><li>Launching {useCase.name} with a clever subject line but weak exclusions.</li><li>Letting attributed revenue hide paying for messages that reach the wrong audience or train shoppers to wait for urgent texts.</li><li>Using one offer for every customer value band.</li><li>Failing to pause or adjust the workflow during launches, stockouts, holidays, and support spikes.</li></ul></article></section> })()}

